Repetition is Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comic, the stubborn effort with which Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of wise, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he considered himself very simple.
When he ended up letting his long-awaited doctrine sweat, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper from Bush’s Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even the phrase "like in Iraq" several times, he did not hesitate, which is more, to use the title of Bush's January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward."
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements to an Iraq consumed by the civil war as being “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, which came from recommendations from campaign commanders, was the only one that was possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers currently don’t talk about Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, that said, objectively speaking, he left his successor a much more favorable final situation than one could hope.
Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again in Afghanistan
Again, it was campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in military contingent, including the Afghan operation commander, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House’s reluctance despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least cheated the general of 10,000 soldiers.
It managed to remove the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though it originally counted on 10,000.
What brings the most trouble in Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and complete this whole process within three years.
Many have doubts that a half increase will bring the same fruits as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the brotherly wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan stands out in the exact opposite – no one can rely on and no treaty is observed.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders day by day according to what arranges them.
Political institutions, although formally founded, will remain the dust behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups given the lack of clarity about the reports, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a “state of prompt action”, which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy confuses by its voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out-of-reality heart can be convinced that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of the war in view of their "swift return home" will bring there a true miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will see it as an indirect acknowledgment of the American defeat.
The recent NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is negatively oriented.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the development of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the heightened sanctions do not have any effect on the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult question of solving the problem using military force.
This will have to be answered, for example, when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will result in a dramatic reversal of the situation in Afghanistan.
The only rust for Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential election, and therefore there is still enough time for him to come up with a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
