Czech Discovery: A Substance That Works on “Tolerant” HIV Viruses Too
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the proliferation of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the enhanced substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality takes, in some cases, over the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on the common variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
There is no cure for AIDS at the moment.
However, the life of patients can be radically extended through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption has a number of side effects.
In addition, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of the development of so-called resistant viruses against which drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Czech Academy of Sciences, the VŠCHT in Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to deal with the virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metal-carborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbonates are a combination of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way than all the drugs used so far and that’s why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers’ work leads them to discover new “improved” substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bonds to the virus’s proteins.
Metal carbonates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
An insidious and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease, there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, it will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little smaller but more reliable.
The effectiveness of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in samples and its resistant variants, obtained from HIV-infected patients.
On the conventional version of the enzyme, the effect of metalocarborans is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however, it does not weaken on resistant versions against which conventional drugs are often ineffective.
