The United Nations Group has draft plans for emissions reduction
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- hitherto characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual complaints -- came back under fire on Friday, due to the publication of a document highlighting ambitious reductions in greenhouse gas emissions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations shouldering most of the burden, in the foreseeable future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles as well as enlightened the way to go.
But it has been seen as a major breakthrough in time-threatening negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world coming to Copenhagen next week.
Written by a special UN working group, the text does not say how much the rich countries would give to the poor to withstand global warming, ongoing and long-term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging economies could decrease their carbon output and what would be the upper limit of global warming that leaders would be willing to tolerate.
It gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the UN Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as being “the full picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, by 25 to 45 percent compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also resumed negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and droughts or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. Representative for Climate Negotiations, has rejected any discussion that requires reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if they weren’t funded by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is becoming harder toward China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions from major developing countries, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the U.S. chief negotiator either lacked "good sense" or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the U.S. would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major global powers at stake, gaps have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting over their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rica delegate, said it wasn’t surprising that major powers are struggling to know who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make major emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who is also climate adviser for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to put pressure to get a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants say that negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which consists of 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission’s climate unit, said the action of the small island states “has put political pressure on the entire political process,” in part because they are now unified and they are calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most issues in court before the heads of government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister came down from their planes and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and news conferences, so they could make claims that will be studied over the next week.
The real picture of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people enter and leave the Congress Palace every day -- of guitar-playing activists presenting nighttime shows mocking countries that they believe are betraying and proposals being drafted and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all major ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the great, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavy trucks are coming.
In Britain, the first train at 225 km/h will redefine Monday syndrome
