Lord Adonis, the Transport Minister, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes on board the first Javelin suburban train outside London.
He hopes the new service will enable Britain to integrate an international network of fast and reliable trains and connect the major conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
Lost small holes will become thriving suburban cities, business travel times will be much shorter, and switching from plane and car to train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic jams on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties are joining this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new railway network, the inevitable battle of planning and fears of environmental hazards risk slashing British high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will hand over its document to Lord Adonis on December 30.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next planned step for the high-speed network.
The new line connecting London to the West Midlands will be drawn within five meters of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment may be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up to 25 meters from the final route.
HS2 is also expected to present three options for a larger high-speed network, going north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred options are highlighted in an Y configuration for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split into two at or near Birmingham, with one branch going west of the Pennines in Manchester and Scotland and another going northeast, to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the best performance option," said a railway professional.
When this is completed, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not be opened before 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a one-hour journey currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making the UK network the fastest in the world.
The initial track is designed to allow trains 400m long and can carry 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can run on a London - Birmingham route.
A terminal that can accommodate 20,000 passengers per hour would be needed.
Given the space constraints, it is planned that an existing station will be expanded to receive the high-speed network.
Rail industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should be put in place, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be made before a general election.
Even if it starts the machine, the network will have to be built part by part.
Trains will first be forced to run out of high-speed lines on existing rails north of Birmingham,ining travel times between London and Scotland of more than three hours.
