Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the major French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence will be in vain.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about making employees adhere to “values” determined from above, as it was once, to impose on consumers products thought by the factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the business, the marketing revolution has put market conquest strategies back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors is constantly coming back!
Demobilization of employees can lead to mortal demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the AI “requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision”; it requires from employees an engagement that the authoritarian management recipes completely contradict.
That’s why we are calling for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
The Importance of Internal Opinion Survey
Will internal polls – such as the questionnaire Orange submitted to its employees – encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I fear that not.
- Firstly because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure eventually, after many turns, to do as a priority ... what it has always done. !
Secondly, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionately to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the great schools of engineers, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American “neurosciences” and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutions of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manipulate the “levers” (sic) of the engagement of executives, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr comforts leaders in a mechanistic governance posture, unsuited to the world of today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern implies adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to realize part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from Motive Functional Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivation.
These studies have demonstrated that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilizing factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resource management back in place.
They thus create a favorable ground for the concerted development of a robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: “Justice war” worthy of praise to Obama
The American right welcomed Barack Obama’s speech in Oslo on Friday, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize has defended the concept of “just war” against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who brokered the award to Obama on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, like Sarah Palin, a former vice president candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Ms. Palin, the right wing of the Republican party, told the daily USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the topic of war "sometimes necessary" in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is of course the last thing I think Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be stopped, he said.
Obama, who inherited two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, spoke in Oslo on Thursday to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "very good work" in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, congratulated the former chairman of the House of Representatives, who appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
On some sides, I found this speech entirely historic, Gingrich said, interviewed during the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected, seen by some as a possible candidate for the Republican inauguration for the 2012 presidential election, said he was pleased to have seen "a leftist president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not deliver a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
For Michael Gerson, a former founder of George W. Bush’s re-converted Washington Post columnist, Obama delivered “a very American speech.”
In addition to presenting himself as a "world citizen" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it," Gerson said.
Among the few on the right to be unconvinced, a Bush-era falcon, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, described the speech as “tinned, glowing and uninspired” on the National Review Online site.
On the left of the president, Democratic representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justify the use of force.
When we wrap war into the notion of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people, he warned.
The center-left press, however, remained praiseful in the place of the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to think that the Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely to Mr. Obama, called his speech "superproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression," the California daily said.
Mr. Obama "pronounced the right speech," the New York Times said, judging it "at the same time dark and edifying."
Roads: three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three marathon negotiations, the road trade unions and TLF, the only employer organization to remain to the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that puts an end to the strike motto and the threat on Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, “rejoiced” with this agreement, after several negotiations, started on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators left early Friday morning, hoping to sign the text of the agreement soon in the morning.
Three employer organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) have been in charge.
But it still took more than six hours from a meeting starting at 11 a.m. for everyone to agree and the text to be signed at 18 a.m.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to companies" and "it was to be feared that it would disrupt the end-of-year holidays," Bussereau said.
The bill foresees an increase in wages by 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and by 2.9% for the highest wages (in international transport).
In the hourly rate, for low wages, "we are going from 8.72 euros to 9,06.
It’s not much, but we’re going very far, said Patrice Clos (FO).
Or we will give orders to our activists that there are no blockades, no blockades of supply centers.
But there can still be some recalcitrants who are not satisfied, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, welcomed "a good deal", although it was "difficult to grant the increases on high wages given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros monthly for the lowest wages and from 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
This is the agreement of common sense and employee respect, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "an historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) called it “an acceptable compromise.”
The agreement also provides for the revaluation of travel costs by 3%, and the general status of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will enable in particular to address the issue of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of 100 million euros in employers' charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the draft rectificative finance law for 2009, voted in the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote on it "in the same term".
The signing of the TLF allows the agreement to apply in the first place to the companies that are members of this organization, and in the second time, to the whole profession, if extended by the Minister of Labour.
It will be done “as soon as possible,” Bussereau assured.
Opposition from employer organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a “trick market” as the 100 million euros “were already promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax.”
The Secretary of State for Transportation forced us to negotiate urgently, not as a conclusion of a shared analysis, but not to upset the turkey-eaters of the next revival.
According to Otre, the agreement “risks digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months.”
