Turkish court dissolves pro-Kurdish party
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday ruled the dissolution of the country’s main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by rage demonstrations in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision is likely to greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just handed out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "house of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the court Hasim Kiliç told the press after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity of Mr. Türk and Mrs. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's assets.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MEPs would leave the Parliament instead of sitting as parliamentarians without a label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accused the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political vitrine of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, assures that it has "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government has just handed out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, to try to curb Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had said a dissolution could lead to a rise in tensions in southeast Anatolia, where numerous protests against the conditions of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan’s detention have degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, a thousand protesters have gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the majority Kurdish-populated city in the southeast.
Law enforcement forces fired tear grenades and used water guns, while demonstrators threw molotov cocktails or stones, with fringes.
Hundreds of people also protested in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Turk said the court’s decision would “deep the despair.”
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
We are opposed to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a total torpedo to the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow may fall.
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very rigorous winter.
But the head of the road clearance and sand clearance service (FES) states that this is not to bother citizens.
This is simply so that agents can test the technology of the vehicles and learn how to properly control them.
According to the meteorologists, this could be the end of the week.
More than 300 officers and 120 vehicles stand ready to fight the snow and frost.
The FES follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr. Brauburger explains that as soon as it begins to snow on the city of Frankfurt and the temperatures fall below zero, large sanding vehicles travel 20 main routes (called routes A) .
This includes busy streets, major arteries, such as Neue Weg and Hanauer Landstraße.
Fire accesses, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as Atzelbergstraße are also included.
FES officers begin their service at three o’clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometers of roadway must be salted with a well-adhesive road melt, within 3 hours maximum.
This is why the FES service begins at 3 a.m. "so that the roads are cleared when the daily migration traffic begins."
This is when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 a.m.
This poses problems, says the head of the road cleaning and sand cleaning service "because no driver is willing to let salt vehicles pass."
Then, if there is no more snow, we take care of access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße.
Secondary roads and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger knows well that this always causes some complaints.
At five o’clock in the morning, the FES pedestrian team sets out to prioritize the areas deemed dangerous and the passages.
As for cycling trails, the FES services can generally not handle them.
Mr. Brauburger says there is a special service in Frankfurt that is responsible for monitoring the state of the bridges between 22:00 and 4:30 p.m.
Because ice is formed very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
Sometimes the police also call for this special service when needed.
The birthplace of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped measured about 2 meters long for 1.50 meters tall, its rear limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with fowls and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have had anything exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to have these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, Pangea, and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds light on the evolution of the early dinosaurs.
In fact, it informs us about the relationships, distribution and characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says they sometimes find a dozen bones in one day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginning of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa from the word of the Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an entirely exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery spectacular, but he says it confirms some theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify early dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Sauridae were divided into three major evolutionary groups: the Theropods (carnivores) which include the Tyrannosaurus and the Velociraptor that appeared later and descended from the birds, the Sauropods, long neck quadrupeds, and those who are related to them, and the Ornithischian herbivores to which species such as the Triceratops and the Stégosaurus belong.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the earliest theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae had small airbags in its bones at the skull level, just like the birds that are the descendants of the theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small airbags in its bones.
Since the relative line of the huge sauropods also possessed airbags and light bones, one can think that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three consecutive waves of migration to North America.
Since the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the Saurians had appeared there.
Consequently, the three major lines of evolution divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. the whole of the emerging lands that formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists has also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not related to it.
The three species could not descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
Of course, there are some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silosaure, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a misconception because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while practically none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how the dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetropods of the secondary age while they originated from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread across the planet thus promoting the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
However, such a success is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction in which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or then, the dinosaurs were better adapted and so they were able to eliminate the competition on the ground.
However, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteor favoured the development of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and that have since been vegetating in the shadow: they were mammals.
