The New Silicon Valley
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, banned from Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a secret weapons research site, under strict surveillance.
Today, with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet “Silicon Valley”.
Important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics are located there.
Since September 2008, representatives of Zelenograd have established ties with Riedberg, a place of science in Frankfurt – with the academic institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were mutual meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a “Protocol of close cooperation”.
The signatories were Moscow Deputy Mayor Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz head of project section for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose focus is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow FIZ companies to enter the growing Russian market.
Instead, Russian scientific societies want to get contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of famous Soviet research institutes and societies.
There are the Moscow Institute of Electrical Engineering, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The municipality was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for arms research.
Zelenograd (literal translation “Green City”) takes its name from the forested hills in the heart of which the research centers are located.
Project S21: a brake for Stuttgart
We can’t put the size of the Stuttgart 21 project high enough.
For its supporters, it is nothing less than “the new heart of Europe”.
S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg into a desperate chaos of construction sites for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born in the spirit of the 1980s.
The head-line stations, with routes ending in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time to be the relics of the 19th-century transportation technology, which had the effect of braking the modern railway traffic because it used to take a lot of time to move locomotives from the back to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that’s what you have to do.
That’s why the headline stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart too: a train passage station, which is located about halfway on the Trans-European Railway Magistrale between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava, hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realization of the S21 project is really going to begin, although the visions of the 1980s have long been incompatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners recognized that the cost of buriing the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
To be honest, the headline stations no longer really pose problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with automotive and car-pilot at both ends.
However, the construction of Stuttgart 21 is now underway alongside the new inter-city line to Ulm.
Local and regional policies have taken advantage of this.
The railway company is on the side because it is the taxpayer who carries the costs of the risk of the largest infrastructure project in the federal republic and not the public company.
From an urbanistic point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
You get an urban space that – if you believe the graphics of computer-generated planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is detrimental.
The passage station and the expansion of the section are designed for a traffic of people to which was attributed – and this is typical of the 1980s – a huge growth.
At the time, there was no competition for cheap flights.
Modern traffic policy should primarily focus on increasing freight traffic as rail transport is much more environmentally friendly than truck transport on the road.
But the new track, with its slopes, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious, indirectly affects many other railway projects.
For example, six billion euros will be engulfed in the Souabe project.
This is the official figure.
Experts believe that 10 to 15 billion is more realistic.
One thing is certain, in the next decade this money will be missing for other points of intersection and clogging in the network.
The Ministry of Transport lists in total sixty major projects.
One of the most important is the expansion of the section through the Rhine valley of 180 good kilometers.
Since 1987 this line has been built slowly.
It would be really urgent to press here deeply on the mushroom.
But the S21 project has the effect of a braking sabotage.
The Rhine valley route is becoming the blockbuster of international freight traffic in the heart of Europe.
The government is reviewing the judgment regarding the airport
In the regional parliament of Wiesbaden, the government of the Land discussed the possibility of appealing the judgment of the Administrative Tribunal of Hesse concerning the ban on night flights.
Economy Minister Dieter Posch (FDP) announced that the CDU/FDP coalition had commissioned experts to review from a legal point of view the ruling of the Administrative Tribunal, which is a document comprising more than 400 pages.
The Court of Cassel had justified in a written document that the Land should adapt the regulation regarding the ban on night flights in case the project for the construction of the northwest landing piste at Frankfurt airport would be realized.
The authorization to land for 17 aircraft between 23:00 and 5:00 in the morning, as envisaged by the government of the Land, is not compatible with the legal protection of citizens against nocturnal air disturbances.
The coalition must have decided by January 4 if it wants to appeal in cassation against the judgment.
The opposition criticizes the deadline and attempts to pressure the government representative to appeal to the Federal Administrative Tribunal in Leipzig.
The leader of the SPD parliamentary group Torsten Schäfer-Gümbel calls on the CDU and FDP to return to their pledge made before the elections to ban night flights.
It is very difficult to be allowed to keep his word, said the leader of the Greens, Tarek Al-Wazir, referring to the FDP’s electoral slogan “We keep our promises.”
Minister Dieter Posch dismissed Schäfer-Gümbel's accusations that the government of the Land is still trying to allow night flights using "avocado and rubber".
It takes time to conduct a precise legal review.
The coalition does not want to make a decision based on a "fast first impression".
The decision must be legally reliable, says Stefan Müller (FDP).
The opposition’s interpretation of its faction’s statements on the ban on night flights is completely wrong.
US banks reimburse allocated aid
Major American banks, severely affected by the crisis, are disconnecting from their ties to the state.
Bank of America announced on Wednesday that it had fully repaid the Treasury $45 billion (more than €30 billion), corresponding to aid granted under the Tarp bailout plan.
U.S. television channel CNBC in a report that Citigroup was also considering reimbursing the aid received.
The banking institutions thus seek to get rid of the restrictions imposed, which accompanied the acceptance of amounts, such as the limitation of bonuses awarded to executives as well as the settlement of higher fees.
The Bank of America launched a capital increase by selling securities to investors that brought it $19 billion in fresh money.
The rest of the sum comes from the bank's cash, which is well filled thanks to the sale of several branches of other sectors.
Last Wednesday evening, Bank of America CEO Kenneth Lewis expressed his gratitude to U.S. taxpayers: the capital injection significantly helped overcome a difficult period.
