Such images and voices do not only appear in mentally ill people or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neuronal activity that allows us to design houses, paint paint paintings or write novels, but sometimes causes the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases it is called visions, in the worst of madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
