Oneiroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the person who lives them and cannot distinguish them from dreams even when they are awake.
The onyroid state of consciousness manifests during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies, as in patients with polyradiculopathy who fully consciously experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces that real situation that affects his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a world change takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation in itself intolerable, an ability to organize which is given to us men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as a salvage of the soul.
He is 49 years old, at the time when his consciousness leaves for a several-day journey after surgery on a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is doomed to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from every room, visits strange places, travels in time.He sees himself as an old man in a railway sanatorium, a robot in his bed watching his health.
He lived in the Middle Ages among nobles who made blood-based drugs.
He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcyclist who takes him back to his homeland, surfs with his hospital bed in the Alps' fog and meets a Korean mafia.
He completely absorbs himself into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys fundamentally differ from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes, describing what he has experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of outer reality are even in a state of wakefulness.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, “can cause a distortion of what we call reality.”
This is an experience that can also be enriching.
