75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for younger women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed in the study “Fertility and professional careers of women in Spain”, conducted by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their professional careers limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of a couple life and the number of children, whether the woman works or not, and the type of job occupied.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get into a couple earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, postpone getting into a couple life and their first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women aged 35-49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after they settled in a couple.This figure increases to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. “These data show that women with a fixed job have needed more time in their lives to get a child, which has led them to push back on union and the arrival of children.
Moreover, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of life together,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that deepens the gap between women’s age of marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the more they get married and have their first child late.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the group aged 35 to 49, those who had completed elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
There is also a difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” says Ms. Delgado.
