Emergency Braking Assistance is Now Mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as will be the case with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a shortage period was fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although, by its way of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The Emergency Braking Assist acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency detected by the system through the driver’s kick.
But it doesn’t always hold the pressure to the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident could not press the brake before the collision, and half of them did not take full advantage of its strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
Assistance intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 pedestrian fatal accidents could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, through a radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to slightly acting on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device puts maximum pressure on the brakes to minimize damage.
