New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a disaster are brought to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage suffered and the cost of repair.
Each accident is different, and calculating the cost of parts and labor time can be a long and complex task.
Calculating the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labor, can take two or three hours.
However, with the help of the latest computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
This is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Disaster assessment and maintenance service providers and solutions dedicate themselves to collecting the information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other competing companies in the field of assessment tools and industry information generation are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is constantly increasing, so that over the past five years, more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car comes out on the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very tough job, as each of the thousand parts of the vehicle must be cataloged and its price recorded.
In addition, a “smart” graphic image of each model is created on which you can click on the different parts of a passenger car.
If this is a massively sold model, the work can be done in a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a low-selling car, it can take three or four months.At present, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have information about Porsche, for example, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
For vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the documentation and development work of the databases, Audatex has eight centers spread around the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in certain brands.
The headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests $90 million each year to develop these databases.
Each month, 2.5 million data is recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this huge flow of information enables these companies to give them different uses and offer different products.
The most common application is for repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing broken parts or to calculate the venous or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does it in the United States.
Looking at the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an idea of the type of support it can provide to professionals in the industry.
The company offers ten different tools, with the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard solution for the assessment of claims, intended for experts.
These include cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it takes into account the estimated repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the paint patterns.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, up to ten times a month.
Then, each insurance company, which performs thousands of experiments, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the complete identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly chain, only through its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle glasses, and AudaSubastas is an open-ended server for the professional sector on the Internet that allows bidding on vehicles declared wasted.
Its statistics service is very useful for identifying trends, conducting geo-demographic analyses or knowing common issues by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a given brand went to the garage for a breakdown or how many suffered serious accidents for a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It markets, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the official parts, prices and times of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for accident assessment, failure or maintenance.
